Look, I'm in my early 30's, and my life spiraling into a truly autismal mess over the last few years has taught me one thing: Luck had no part in it, aside from the bad luck of being born an autist in sucky times to be an autist.

It seems, to me, that confidence is key. I've managed to have it at certain points in my life, and life became better because of it. I can look at my bad habits, my bad decisions, and see that it comes back to being insecure, to not knowing what I want, to being unable to commit to anything. That's made worse by my literal autism, of course, but when you get down to it that's the basis.

I'm here because I used to write pretty seriously as a hobby. I stopped, because my confidence in my ability took a big dive. And you know what I've seen in the past few years? People who were first published and rose to be household names in my favorite genre in the years I had been inactive. And if only I'd have had discipline and confidence, I could have been one of those people.

It's not easy to suddenly start looking at yourself differently. Believe me, I know. I haven't been living life particularly well. But it doesn't have to happen suddenly, and you're down for the count in any case if you give up before starting. And really, you're always going to be the oldest you've always been, so it always feels too late. When I look back, I felt exactly the same way when I was 25 as I do now. Always some excuse to call myself "too old" for something.

If you want to change, pick something small, and start now. You're almost certainly bound to fall back on old habits, but that's OK. You still made that progress.
